sentence: Remember how long it seemed to take the Dow to hit 20K?
It finally crossed and stayed above that mark on January 25th, approximately a month after people first started talking about it.
21K was much easier!
There wasn't a lot of talk about this milestone last night; the market was way more concerned with President Trump's first speech to Congress.
His performance was very well received, and the market just took off.
Not only did the Dow make up the nearly 200 points to get to 21K, it did so with aplomb by adding over 100 points more.
The index jumped 1.46% on Wednesday (or 303 points) to 21,115.6.
Equally as impressive was the S&P.
The index first eclipsed 2300 on February 9, and now less than a month later it's knocking on the door of 2400.
It was up 1.37% to nearly 2396.
The NASDAQ increased 1.35% to 5904, completing the trifecta of new highs.
President Trump didn't offer many details on a pro-growth agenda that this market REALLY wants, but his speech was positive and devoid of controversy.
For a wild card president like this one, that was good enough for stocks.
Plus, he did touch on tax cuts and infrastructure spending.
So we're still waiting for the specifics, but feeling better about it.
Insider Trader: Tracey added two beaten-down stocks on Wednesday that have captured the attention of insiders.
But first, the editor had to sell a couple names to make room…and they were both solid profits.
The portfolio got out of Church & Dwight (CHD) for a 12.4% return and the remaining half of Kratos (KTOS) for a profit of 8.3%.
United Insurance Holdings (UIHC) is one of the new buys.
This small cap property & casualty insurance company will have a bigger footprint after merging with American Coastal.
Plus, analysts are encouraged by its future outlook.
Insiders are encouraged too, and last week three of them bought shares (the Chief Revenue Officer, the Chief Underwriting Officer and a director).
Tracey is putting 6.5% into UIHC, which is about half of the cash from the above-mentioned sells.
The other half of the proceeds went to SM Energy (SM), as Tracey is seeing real opportunity for this weak sector moving forward.
This mid-cap explorer has made several moves to weather this uncooperative environment, yet shares are still down about 28% year-to-date.
But four insiders (the President & CEO, the General Counsel and 2 directors) see an opportunity, and on Monday they all bought shares.
Get all the info on these moves in the complete commentary, and don't be surprised if Tracey buys more energy names down the road.
Reitmeister Trading Alert:"Nobody ever got poor selling a stock for a profit," said Mr. Reitmeister; a lesson his son Steve learned very well and put into practice today.
With Thor Industries (THO) surging to new highs just a few days in front of its earnings report on Monday, the editor thought that now was a great time to trim the position and take a 14.3% profit.
The portfolio will keep a 6.2% allocation in the name.
Game Changers: We're now less than two weeks away from this portfolio being retired from the ZU lineup, and Brian is determined to go out with a lot of green.

On Wednesday, he sold six names…all for profits: Jabil Circuit (JBL, +8.9%), FutureFuel (FF, +6.3%), KeyCorp (KEY, +5.8%), Lincoln Electric Holdings (LECO, +5.1%), Kulicke and Soffa Industries (KLIC, +3.1%) and Green Dot Corp. (GDOT, +1.8%).
The editor is holding onto some other names over the weekend to get the biggest possible returns.
Read more in the full write-up.
Options Trader: Kevin remains very bullish on his CME Group (CME) position, but the stock is taking its sweet time getting to the target and is now just 15 days away from expiration.
So the editor wants more time.
He sold to close the two March 125.00 Calls for a 10% profit, but then repositioned into three small June $5 spreads.
Specifically, Kevin bought to open 3 June 130.00 Calls AND sold to open 3 June 135.00 Calls.
Now, if CME can close at or above $135 by the new mid-June expiration, then this position will bring a gain of 212%.
Read the full write-up for more on these moves.
TAZR Trader: The portfolio bought 7% allocations in Salesforce.com (CRM) and j2 Global, Inc. (JCOM) today.
These companies are both leaders in the Software as a Service (SaaS) space, which is one of the fastest growing components of the cloud services market.
Make sure to read all the details of these new additions in the complete commentary.
Zacks Counterstrike:"A doozy of a day as the Dow surged 300 points, the S&P was up over 1.3% and the Nasdaq was up 1.35%.
We were way overdue for a blow off top or a sell off, and today we got the move higher.
Trump's speech last night didn't give a lot of details, so as I mentioned last night, the markets should have sold off.
"However, his tone was much different than the tone he has shown through twitter and previous appearances.
A lot of talking heads today were saying that he sounded Presidential for the first time and I have to agree.
"We need a pullback, but do we get one?
For now, it looks as if the markets have no interest in selling off.
There is simply no catalyst and markets have full faith that Trump will get the job done.
So we will have to wait and see.
In the meantime, long and strong is the right way to be."

-- Jeremy Mullin
